This action contributes to the original initiative “EUTF-IOM initiative for migrant protection and reintegration in Africa”. The initiative covers 14 countries and is made up of specific actions in the 14 countries where it will be implemented. The activities will therefore be mainly implemented at national level but will be coordinated at the regional level in order to ensure harmonization of activities in the different countries and to ensure coherence of the initiative.

This project will enable the first stage implementation of the new national immigration service strategy by equipping and supporting five state command offices with a personnel training and resource centre, as envisioned and defined in the strategy, to begin serving that command’s personnel with newly-designed and highly focused short training programmes (averaging four days), supported by the local training focal point serving as a facilitator, and by providing tailored complementing self-directed learning materials and resources – including computer-based curricula.

IOM’s response to Typhoon Rai (Odette) aims to mitigate the impact of the typhoon on the most vulnerable populations, which has multi-sectoral approaches to address their outstanding needs of shelter, water, sanitation and hygiene, and mental health and psychosocial support. Target communities include the most vulnerable and hard-to-reach communities in Southern Leyte in Eastern Visayas Region and as well as in Dinagat Islands, and Surigao del Norte (including Siargao Island) in Caraga Region.

Through this project, IOM supports the resettlement process of selected individuals under the resettlement scheme of the Government of Canada, with the provision of transportation from the point of departure to the final destination in Canada. This includes assistance with travel within the country of residence, as well as international travel, assistance at the time of departure, including immigration and airline checks, assistance in points of transit, providing escorts for the resettlement travel, when needed, and assistance to un-accompanied minors and people with special needs.

This project seeks to provide integrated multisectoral lifesaving and life-sustaining assistance to vulnerable populations affected by the Syrian crisis. IOM's programs are needs-driven, rights-based, and gender-, age-, and vulnerability-sensitive. IOM will maintain a strong focus on humanitarian principals and accountability throughout the project. The project will also address the immediate humanitarian needs of those affected by the crisis in Syria, while supporting longer-term resilience. IOM works with a network of partners, and ensures its actions are coordinated at all levels with relevant stakeholders and interagency forums. This project will particularly focus on the shelter, non-food items needs of affected populations.

This project will further strengthen the existing IOM voluntary return mechanism in Japan through continued facilitation of safe and humane return home for irregular migrants. Within the objective of contributing to improving the protection and sustainable reintegration of migrants and migration management of the Government of Japan by providing assisted voluntary return and reintegration services as alternative to long-term detention or forcible removal/deportation, the project's target outcomes are; migrants with irregular status in Japan who wish to return are able to do so safely, voluntarily and with dignity, and beneficiaries are economically self-sufficient, psychosocially well, and socially integrated in their communities through IOM reintegration assistance.

This project contributes to enhancing peace, security and stability through rebuilding trust between law enforcement officials and communities; and a conducive environment for returns through strengthened social cohesion and increasing access to rights and political representation. To address these objectives, IOM will increase the capacity of law enforcement officials and the ability of the community to engage with one another to identify and resolve security issues through the Community Policing approach, as well as increase interagency coordination on border security issues. This project will also strengthen the participation of the Yazidi community in transitional justice mechanisms development, and increase inter community cohesion and political representation of Yazidis. IOM will support Yazidis and other vulnerable families to access housing, land and property rights as well as enhanced tenure security and rights.

The Horn of Africa and Yemen is a region of origin, transit, and destination for hundreds of thousands of migrants, the majority of whom travel in an irregular manner, often relying on smugglers to facilitate movement along the Eastern Route (originating from Ethiopia and Somalia and transiting through Somalia, Djibouti and Yemen) with the intention of crossing the Gulf of Aden towards the Gulf States to seek better livelihood opportunities. The vulnerabilities of the migrants are one of the specific drivers to migration and determinants of IOM's response through the Regional Migrants Response Plan. Through this project, IOM is providing lifesaving assistance to vulnerable migrants and host communities including protection assistance and services.

The project aims at contributing to the sustainable reintegration in their countries of origin of returnees from Switzerland. Possibilities of reintegration assistance may range from professional reintegration (income-generating activity), housing assistance, training/education, cash for care, cash for shelter with potential additional medical assistance.

This project regulates what services IOM provides to persons who have the right to stay in Switzerland and have been considered eligible by SEM to bring their family members to Switzerland. IOM will carry out pre-departure “fitness to travel” health assessments, transportation services as well as other services related to family reunification as required by the SEM and agreed upon by IOM.
